{# FAQ #}
<section class="py-12">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <h2 class="section-heading mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <details class="card p-5 group" open>
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Why is Ireland so popular for tech companies?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Ireland combines EU membership, a favorable corporate tax rate (15%), an English-speaking workforce, and a strong legal framework. This makes it the ideal European headquarters for US tech giants. Google, Meta, Apple, Microsoft, Salesforce, Stripe, and many others have significant operations in Dublin, creating a deep talent pool and rich ecosystem.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What is the Critical Skills Employment Permit?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The <strong>Critical Skills Employment Permit</strong> is Ireland's premium work permit for high-demand occupations. Most tech roles qualify. It requires a minimum salary of €38,000 for roles on the critical skills list (€64,000 for other eligible roles). Key benefits include immediate family reunification rights and eligibility for a Stamp 4 (unrestricted work permission) after just two years.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What's the housing situation in Dublin?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Dublin's rental market is competitive and can be expensive — expect €1,800–€2,500/month for a one-bedroom in the city center. Many professionals initially look at areas like Rathmines, Ranelagh, or Drumcondra for better value. It's advisable to secure temporary accommodation first, then search in person. Some employers offer housing assistance or relocation stipends to help with the transition.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Can I bring my family to Ireland?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Yes. The Critical Skills Employment Permit allows immediate family reunification — your spouse or partner can apply for a Stamp 1G visa, which permits them to work in Ireland without needing a separate work permit. Dependent children can also join you. This is one of the most generous family reunion policies in Europe.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

